                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 (China) American Radio Service/74:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-08T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 8 [<hi rend="italic">7?</hi>], 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 8—9:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>434. Department’s 181, October 31, 7 p.m., American Radio Service.
                    Representations made yesterday to Japanese Embassy here include a request that
                    steps be taken by the responsible Japanese authorities to effect an immediate
                    return of the seized radio equipment and files to the custody of the American
                    Consular Court at Tientsin.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department. Repeated to Chungking. Code text by air mail to Tokyo and
                    by mail to Tientsin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
